snippet.textDisplay: Being from an older generation, to me this is on a level of John Lennon's untimely death.  Not just for the magnitude of the tragedy (because both men were pillars and icons in their respective spheres) but for the senselessness and capricious nature of the tragedy.  It's like waking up and learning, hearing, reading that 2 + 2 now equals 3.  You know it isn't true.  That is doesn't make sense.  That it goes against your nature and understanding of how things ought to be.  But the powers that be say 'Don't care.  It's now 3.  Deal with it'.  The only remedy is to take it a day at a time.  And, to paraphrase Kobe himself, ".. some days are going to be hard. So hard, you want to quit.  But on those days when you can't run, you just gotta put one foot in front of the other and keep going".

snippet.textDisplay:
I hope nobody takes this the wrong way. Growing up Shaq was my favorite basketball player (playing for Orlando). Eventually Kobe became my favorite. I haven’t watched basketball in years. I found out about this on a hockey forum and could not believe it.

Being that I haven’t watched basketball in years, it’s shocking to me how much this news hurt.

What I have trouble understanding is why we value celebrity lives so much more than regular people. Yes people mention the other people who died in the crash. But people are heartbroken over Kobe. The tributes are about Kobe (and his daughter in some of them).

I’m not trying to diminish what Kobe meant to people. He meant more to me than I realized. I just kind of wish that people grieve as much for the normal folks as those that are famous.

I know this may not make sense to anyone who reads this, but, I don’t believe in God. However, I hope that there is a heaven, and I hope all of those people that died go there. What I’m saying may not make sense is, I say I don’t believe in God, but I still say God bless them.
